<p class="drop-cap">If the sacraments are the lungs of the Church, prayer is breathing itself. Eastern Christianity does not treat prayer as one activity among many — something you do at meals or bedtime, a line item on the spiritual to-do list. Prayer is the <em>atmosphere</em> of the Christian life. Without it, the sacraments become rituals, the icons become decorations, and theology becomes an academic exercise. With it, everything else comes alive. The Fathers of the East had a phrase for this: pray without ceasing. They meant it literally.</p>

<p>This may sound impossible. We are, after all, people with jobs, families, and grocery lists. But the Eastern tradition has, over two millennia, developed a remarkably practical approach to unceasing prayer — one that begins not with superhuman effort but with a single sentence, repeated until it sinks from the mind into the heart.</p>

<h2>The Jesus Prayer</h2>

<p>At the center of Eastern prayer life stands five words that have shaped more saints than any theological treatise: <strong>"Lord Jesus Christ, have mercy on me."</strong> Sometimes expanded to "Lord Jesus Christ, Son of God, have mercy on me, a sinner" — this is the Jesus Prayer, and it is the foundation stone of Eastern spirituality.</p>

<p>The prayer is deceptively simple. It contains the whole of Christian theology in a single breath: the lordship of Christ, His divinity, the reality of human need, and the appeal to mercy that is the only appropriate response of a creature before its Creator. To pray it once is to say something true. To pray it a thousand times is to begin to <em>live</em> inside that truth.</p>

<Pullquote attribution="— The Way of a Pilgrim, 19th-century Russian spiritual classic">
  By the grace of God I am a Christian, by my deeds a great sinner, and by calling a homeless wanderer. I have one possession — the Jesus Prayer. That is my wealth, my treasure, and my joy.
</Pullquote>

<p>The Jesus Prayer is traditionally accompanied by a <strong>prayer rope</strong> (<em>chotki</em> or <em>komboskini</em>) — a knotted cord, usually of wool, with 33, 50, or 100 knots. The rope serves the same purpose as the Western rosary: it gives the hands something to do while the mind focuses on God. But unlike the rosary, which moves through a cycle of different prayers and mysteries, the prayer rope carries one prayer, repeated. The repetition is the point. As the anonymous author of <em>The Way of a Pilgrim</em> discovered, the prayer eventually begins to pray itself — running like a quiet stream beneath the surface of daily life.</p>

